<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72420" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">
Body length, males 2.50-2.70 mm. Vertex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7346146" captionText="Figure 4. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Habitus, dorsal view B. Habitus, lateral view C. Head and thorax, dorsal view D. Face." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/568240" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">4</figureCitation>
A) light yellow, with pair of small black spots. Coronal suture short, with two irregular black markings on both sides (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7346146" captionText="Figure 4. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Habitus, dorsal view B. Habitus, lateral view C. Head and thorax, dorsal view D. Face." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/568240" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">4</figureCitation>
A and C). Eyes greyish-black. Pronotum yellowish, with symmetrical pale-yellow oval impressed patches medially, (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7346146" captionText="Figure 4. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Habitus, dorsal view B. Habitus, lateral view C. Head and thorax, dorsal view D. Face." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/568240" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">4</figureCitation>
A and C). Scutellum yellow, with black lateral triangles, transverse impression distinct. Face light brownish-yellow, frontoclypeus with black patches at sides basally; anteclypeus dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7346146" captionText="Figure 4. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Habitus, dorsal view B. Habitus, lateral view C. Head and thorax, dorsal view D. Face." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/568240" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">4</figureCitation>
D). Forewing with orange and grey patches. Abdominal apodemes small, extended to hind margin of 3rd sternite (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7346154" captionText="Figure 5. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Male pygofer, lateral view B. Pygofer dorsal appendage, lateral view C. Subgenital plate D. Style E. Aedeagus, ventral view F. Aedeagus, lateral view G. Connective H. Abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593917" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">5</figureCitation>
H).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72420" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
Pygofer lobe broad, with numerous microtrichia and fine setae scattered near caudal part and dorsal margin. Pygofer dorsal appendage expanded basally, tapering to apex and hook-like apically (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7346154" captionText="Figure 5. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Male pygofer, lateral view B. Pygofer dorsal appendage, lateral view C. Subgenital plate D. Style E. Aedeagus, ventral view F. Aedeagus, lateral view G. Connective H. Abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593917" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">5</figureCitation>
A and B). Subgenital plate short, wide and midfield slightly concave, with three macrosetae, numerous peg-like setae along dorsal margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7346154" captionText="Figure 5. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Male pygofer, lateral view B. Pygofer dorsal appendage, lateral view C. Subgenital plate D. Style E. Aedeagus, ventral view F. Aedeagus, lateral view G. Connective H. Abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593917" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">5</figureCitation>
C). Style apex expanded, &quot;curved neck&quot; area slender, pre-apical lobe obvious, enlarged (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7346154" captionText="Figure 5. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Male pygofer, lateral view B. Pygofer dorsal appendage, lateral view C. Subgenital plate D. Style E. Aedeagus, ventral view F. Aedeagus, lateral view G. Connective H. Abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593917" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">5</figureCitation>
D). Pre-atrium of aedeagus little expanded in lateral view, aedeagus shaft slender, with pair of &quot;finger-like&quot; processes arising from base of shaft and extending outwards, bifurcated into two branches apically (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7346154" captionText="Figure 5. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Male pygofer, lateral view B. Pygofer dorsal appendage, lateral view C. Subgenital plate D. Style E. Aedeagus, ventral view F. Aedeagus, lateral view G. Connective H. Abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593917" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">5</figureCitation>
E and F). Connective Y-shaped, two lateral arms and stem developed, median anterior lobe well developed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7346154" captionText="Figure 5. Mitjaevia ramosa sp. n. A. Male pygofer, lateral view B. Pygofer dorsal appendage, lateral view C. Subgenital plate D. Style E. Aedeagus, ventral view F. Aedeagus, lateral view G. Connective H. Abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e72420.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593917" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">5</figureCitation>
G).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72420" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">
The new species is named from the Latin word 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“ramosus”">&quot;ramosus&quot;</normalizedToken>
, referring to the aedeagal shaft with two bifurcated branches at apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="72420" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Distant" baseAuthorityYear="1918" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Mitjaevia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mitjaevia diana" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Mitjaevia diana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Distant, W L" journalOrPublisher="Coleoptera Staphylinidae" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420" pagination="411 - 691" refId="B7346087" refString="Distant, W L, 1918. The fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma. 7. Rhynchota (Homoptera: appendix. Heteroptera: addenda). Coleoptera Staphylinidae 116 (1420): 411 - 691" title="The fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma. 7. Rhynchota (Homoptera: appendix. Heteroptera: addenda)" volume="116" year="1918">Distant 1918</bibRefCitation>
), but differs in having the &quot;finger-like&quot; processes arising from base of aedeagal shaft and extending outwards; two bifurcated branches at apex; connective Y-shaped and stem developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="72420">Distribution.</emphasis>
Guizhou Province.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
